## What Problem This Solves

Resolves a Google provider compatibility problem where the bundled Google plugin exposes the Gemini CLI harness through direct runtime plugin registration by default, even though the supported default Google model path should remain the API-backed `google` provider.

The affected workflow is Google provider setup/runtime selection. This PR keeps existing setup-registry `google-gemini-cli` backend compatibility available while requiring explicit operator opt-in for direct bundled runtime registration of the Gemini CLI provider/backend.

## Why This Change Was Made

The change makes the Google provider boundary explicit: `google` remains the API-backed Google AI Studio/Gemini provider, `google-vertex` remains the Vertex provider, and `google-gemini-cli` is treated as an optional local CLI harness.

The opt-in is controlled by `OPENCLAW_ENABLE_GOOGLE_GEMINI_CLI_HARNESS=1`. This applies only to direct bundled runtime plugin registration. The setup-registry default for `google-gemini-cli` remains available so existing setup-only backend resolution continues to work.

The PR also aligns manifest metadata, onboarding copy, provider contract copy, public Google provider docs, and docs navigation with that compatibility policy.

## User Impact

Users configuring the default Google provider continue to see the API-backed Google path instead of being directed toward Gemini CLI OAuth by default.

Existing `google-gemini-cli` setup/backend resolution remains available through the setup-registry compatibility path. Operators who want direct bundled runtime registration of the Gemini CLI provider/backend can set `OPENCLAW_ENABLE_GOOGLE_GEMINI_CLI_HARNESS=1`.

